segments.text: for, you know, include your name and age and something about what you do in this area.
Well, I'm D.L.
Peters, Doug Peters, and I've lived right around in, in four bars of here all my life.
I'll be, let's see, I was born in 98, I'll be 70, 77 this next birthday.
Won't I always?
And, uh,
But I spent 10 years in the crime academy working for my brother in the ranch over there.
And we moved over there in 33 and moved back here in 43 and built this home here and got through it in 44 and been right here ever since.
And that's our old home place right across the road there.
And we moved down there when I was seven years old.
And I'll never forget that.

we moved up there one day and school had started you know and and I never had been to school and so when children them days all walked you know to school and there's two families lived on this way so when they came along when they told me to send me out there to go to school with them when we got on down the road down to Hunter when they they older kids you know got to tell me about what all they gonna do to me that day you know and they'll been to school I turned around and
That'd take me on a scoot, but like I told you a while ago, I didn't go long enough.
Who were the first people in your family to move to this area?
Where did they come from?
Do you have any idea?
No, I just don't know much about my people now.
As far as, you know, I was born and raised, like I said, right around here.
Where did your dad come from?
He was staying away.
He was here.
I see.
Now you're involved in farming and some ranching too, aren't you?
No farming, just ranching.
Have you noticed a lot of changes in the ranching methods or techniques since you moved here?
Since you can remember?
Tell me something about how they've changed.
Well, way back on, you know, you didn't.
The only way you fed in the cattle most when I was a kid was to cut moss trees for them.
That's how we feed them.
Well, some people did feed cottonseed, you know, just whole cottonseed to the milk cows, something like that.
But cattle on the range, the only feed they ever got is when you cut out a moss tree and they got the moss off of it.
Of course, that changed up a lot, just a whole lot.
We started out feeding cottonseed
cake when we first started feeding cattle.
And we'd feed them about three times a week and give them two or three pounds a piece, you know.
But now we feed the blocks and mineral blocks, stuff like that, just put it out once a week.
It's a whole lot easier that way.
I guess just as good as the other two.
Being involved in ranching, do you remember any particularly bad years for weather?
You know, droughts, or floods, or tornadoes, or things like that you can recall?
When were they?
1925 was one real bad drought.
It just sure was that bad.
We've had about three of them, but I can't remember what years there were now.
Can you tell me some more about the 1925 and what you did and what really went on around here during that?
Of course, I was a young fellow then, and we didn't have any of the water cleanouts.
You know, we didn't have any water.
Of course, didn't have any grass either much, but just, you got to have water.
You sure got to have that with Kevin.
And them days, it sounds funny to say that there's some country down on this Minnesota River them days that never had been fenced.
It's just open country.
We took them cattle down there to the river.
Of course, there's water in the river down there, but our place, Wixon Creek, goes through here.
And the water all dried up and we didn't have any water.
We got a man, a well man out there, my daddy did, to drill a deep well, you know, and we was gonna try to hook a gasoline pump onto it and water them that way.
And he came out there with a big outfit and left it strapped in old water.
And we moved the cattle on down to the river then and just run them outside and fed them a little cotton seed cake and cut elm trees for them.
They'd eat the leaves off of the elm trees and fed them a little cake.
Of course, we had plenty of water down there.
The river was in the hole, but it hadn't dried up.
Of course, we used to run hogs outside, you know.
That's pretty good business for a while, too.
Well, let me change the subject just a little bit.
Do you remember any real famous people ever coming to the Bryan College Station area?
Politicians or ministers or whatever that were really well-known nationally that you can remember coming here?
Well, I don't, Judge Barron, I was telling you about just a while ago, I feel like he's done as much for this county as any man I can think of.
Tell me something about what you mean.
Well, he's a Christian man, and he stands for the principles, you know, the right thing.
And he's had a big influence in that way.
I'm not familiar with the man.
Just tell me something about him.
I don't know anything about him.
Well, he's a lawyer, and he was judge of this county for several years.
When did he start being judge?
Oh, I can't remember.
Way back in the day.
Way back in the day.
But he's meant a lot to this county.
He sure has, I think.
We're looking at that picture up there on the wall that you showed me from 1910, downtown Bryan.
Tell me something about the people in 1910 in Bryan.
What did most of them do?
What kept them around here?
Was College Station here then?
Oh yeah, College Station.
Boy, I can remember.
When was college...
When was it organized and started over there?
The university?
It was in the 1860s?
With the Hatch Act?
I think that's right.
It's been there ever since I was
I don't remember, I know.
Well, back them days, you know, you went everywhere horseback or in a buglet or wagon or something like that.
You didn't, wasn't in an automobile.
And on that, in that picture up there, there's one old car sitting there.
Do you notice that?
Yeah, I see it.
I sure do.
That's the only cars in the county, I reckon, in 1910.
And I remember when they had a trolley car
They used to run from Bryan to College and out there, what we call Midway now, you know where that is?
Uh-huh, sure do.
Martin's Barbecue's in Long Lake, that's Midway.

And they had a big, built a big tank out there at Lake and made a swimming place, you know, where you'd go out there and go swimming and then they had rods of different kinds out there, kind of like a
on the order of a carnival or something like that, you know, a pleasure deal.
So that was a big deal.

Them days, of course, the boys would come into the Brine to the picture show, the A&M boys, and they used to turn the Allen Academy boys and the A&M boys all loose on Saturday evenings, you know, and they could come in there, but they quit doing that.
I heard that there's too many boys out there
at one time, so Allen then went to turn it out on Monday.
On Mondays, having a Monday holiday and a Saturday.
But you did that for a good while.
Tell me something about, remember the Depression?
Oh, you bet.
You were here then.
Tell me what conditions were like during that time around here.
That's my daughter up there, Miss Bell.
What did you say his name was?
Barfield, Carl Barfield.
Nice to meet you.
Nice to meet you too.
tell you what now.
Tell me something about the Depression.
What went on around there?
What did people do?
How were people thinking about it during that time?
Well, it is tough.
But, of course, country people, you know, we, cattle got out to nothing.
You couldn't get nothing for them.
Farm products, you couldn't get nothing for that.
But

I guess in a way the country people fared better than the city people because we had gardens and had plenty of meat to eat you know and as far as uh we didn't have any money but we did have plenty to eat.
But it wasn't a way for us to get over the money them did.
What did most people around here do at that time during the depression?
They farmed and ranched.
When I was a kid this whole community was in farming.
What kind of crops?
Cotton and corn.
That was the main crop.
Cotton was the money crop.
Of course, the corn, they had to have that to feed the stock on, you know.
You know, I work with insects.
It's my profession.
I'd be interested in knowing if you remember the first boll weevil that was reported in this area.
No, I can't remember that.
Do you remember any particularly bad years for insects?
You finally caught it, didn't you?
No, I don't remember what particular year it was, but I do remember when I was just a kid, I didn't hear anything about it, but I don't remember when it started.
They were mostly down in the Brazilians.
Yeah, it started more so down in there, because that was a cotton country more than so it is.
And the Depression, didn't we live over in Barnes County then?
Oh, we live down here.
Well, here's two pictures up here.
I don't guess they do you any good.

Do you remember any particularly big events, like political meetings or community picnics or anything of that sort that took place around here that really attracted a lot of people and were really big things?
The Hoods Brigade.
We had Hoods Brigade.
All the men and boys had to let their
Beards grow out and all, and the women wore colonial dresses, and bonnets, you know.
That was the hoods we gave.
Yeah, but I can't remember much about it.
Things way back yonder, I can remember a lot cleaner than I can, but just a lot of things that happen now, I can't remember nothing about it in a year or two.
Well, how far back there are you talking about remembering?
Well, like that 1910 now.
What do you remember?
When you see that picture, what do you think of?
I just think of one thing that I used to really enjoy.
Those bottom farmers was all down in the brown part of them, you know, down Jones Bridge Road and all that part of the country.
They brought all their cotton and everything to Brown.
Of course, they had gin down there, but then they'd haul it.
Brown had it compressed, you know, and stored here.
And they hauled all their groceries, all their supplies from here back down there.
And big farmers had commissaries.
But the thing I can tell you is that those teams, they were big bottom farmers that had six and maybe some of them, a few of them, eight mules to one wagon.
And they colored people in.
They could really handle them mules.
You know how wide Street Brown is.
They'd put one line on that mule and they'd be riding one to the wheel wagging you.
And they'd put one line on the lead mule and they could just swing that wagon around there and back it up to the porch there and load it.
And I got a lot of kick out of it.
I'm just watching them.
That's one of the
One thing that I can remember more so than nearly anything, and I've seen steers on the street.
There's an old boy up north of Brown.
He used to drive steers a lot.
I've seen him a lot of times.
I just enjoyed them.
And they'd have little bells on the mules, on the lead mule.
Yeah.
And a torso, red torso.
It looked good to me.
I got a lot of kick out of just watching that.
Do you remember anything, anyone ever telling you about slavery in this area, about owning slaves or anything of that nature in the Bryan College Station area?
No, I don't believe I can.
This piece of land that you live on right here, who lived here before you did?
Do you know anything about these people?
Well, this particular spot, I don't believe anybody ever lived right on it, but we got some men right out there that were colored from it.
But there's a, there's a white fellow that owned the head of him, but I can't, he was a doctor.
I mean, doctor, but he, you know, he's, well, I, I think he'd served the term in the pen.
And he got out in the wheelchair.
He had a son, and he and his wife and son, but he never did practice medicine here.
But he lived right out there.
But after that, though, after he didn't stay there,
Seemed like a year or two, I can't remember.
But there's an old colored fella bought it.
He and his wife lived there, didn't have any children.
And that's all.
But now this, there was a house right down yonder where that one was then, and this land, this old colored fella had three acres out there.
And the 17 acres belonged to a man by the name of Freeman that lived down there then, and that's as far back as I can remember.
anybody.
He's living there as far as I can remember.
But.
You know my grandfather used to tell me of back in the late 1890s early 1900s of actually seeing some of the old west saloon the saloons and the the gunfights actually.
He saw one or two of those he would relate.
Did you ever witness anything like this?
No of course I had saloons then they don't ever
They were cornered, Brian, in 1910.
Tell me, you remember anything about them?
I mean, at all?
No, I don't.
I never did.
There's a fellow who run a hamburger joint in one of them, and he stood right in it.
I mean, he had to stand right in the front door.
And kids, they wasn't allowed to go in the flume, but we could go up to that front door and get hamburgers and things like that.
But I can't never remember maybe but once or twice ever going in a saloon back in them days.
Of course, now when you go to eat, you go in a beer jar.
You know, they usually had a beer or something like that.
But I've never seen any fights like that or any trouble like that.
If you had to pick out one or two things at their events or whatever that have happened in this area,
in your lifetime that really stand out or that have impressed you, what would you talk about?
I can't even remember.
Just take a second and think about something.
I'm sure you must have experienced a tremendous amount since you've been here.
Well, there's one thing that just comes to my mind, I don't know whether, but anyhow,
Well, back yonder we used to drive cattle from, buy cattle over yonder at Riverside, the other side of Huntsville, you know where that is?
And we'd drive them, drive them there over here.
And then from here over to Caldwell, we, that's when I was a young fella, and we bought cattle over there, and we'd bought and sell and sold.
And we'd go over there and buy a bunch of cattle and drive them here, or to Welborn over here,
and my friend and I, we was in together.
And I never will forget one time we brought a bunch of cattle from over there and we came through Pinewood from the other side of, going to Huntsville over there.
What's the name of that place this side of Huntsville?
Shire Oak, and then they, well, we came through Pinewood there, just open country, you know, Pinewood,
They had a railroad them days going through Carlisle.
You know where Carlisle is?
No, I don't.
It's the old Carlisle Drive County on 30 going to Boyd's Huntsman.
And one time we had a bunch of cattle.
We were just about to the railroad track, and a train was coming.
And an engineer, I reckon, thought he'd give us a little scare.
And he went to blowing the whistle, and them cattle just, man, they broke out.
And there's a home that's built like this is a fence going down the railroad right-of-way.
The right-of-way was here.
Well, there's a home right against this fence with a porch sticking out over in there right-of-way like.
You know, like this is a house with a porch that stands out here.
And there's two children swinging out on the porch in one of these swings that swing up from the ceiling down.
And a cow run across that porch and slipped and knocked them two kids out of that swing, and they went crawling in the house.
But I think about that every once in a while, about how dangerous it was.
But we finally got them all together.
But that's about it.
Just thinking back to it.
You mentioned the railroad.
What do you remember about the railroad in relationship to Bryan College Station?
But of course the railroad's been here ever since I can remember.

There used to be a, of course we, you know in them days you didn't, my grandfather lived in Bryan, and I'd get to go out there and spend the night with him once in a while, and the first picture show I ever saw,
Was that right across from the old Dixie Theater, what do you call that?
You remember when that was?
No, no, it must have been...
I'm 77 years old, must have been...
I imagine I was maybe 12, 14 years old, something like that.
You were born in 1898?
Yeah, yeah.
I imagine I do not know.
Tell me something about the women of these times when you were growing up.
Perhaps your mother or what did they do?
Were they just mostly around the house or what was really their role?
Well, yeah, most of the women that I was associated with, their role was just housekeeping and kind of looking after the family, you know.
That's most of it.
Well, can you tell me something about your immediate family, or how many brothers and sisters, and what they all did, or what?
Well, I had got two brothers and a sister living there, and one brother died when he was around 21 years old.
But we was all raised right here, every one of them.
Well done.
And two brothers lived, one brother lived right over here.
in this big house, and the other one lived in Brown.
Sister lived in Austin, and that's as far as we ever got away from here to live.
You know, your wife, or you mentioned earlier that you go to church quite often.
Apparently you're a religious man.

Can you tell me something about the churches in this area and how they got started, or what the story was with what kind of religions, or where are you, and how long have you been, and that sort of thing?
Well, the church is, our church is right up here on this 30, you know where you turn?

Well, that's our church, and it was moved from down, it's Bethel Church now, but it's moving down the road there, it's off of the road, the highway, and we live back down towards, we went to Steve Haller Church until then.
I was seven years old and then, as I told you a while ago, we moved up here.
And they had a vote going, you know, they're trying to move the church up where it is now, and some of them was in favor of it and some of them were not.
And so my dad and mother never did take part until after they got it settled, when they voted to move it up here.
Well, they joined this church up here after they got that settled.

and so it's that's i remember when they built it up here but the old church i remember it too down there but i i remember going there some but that's about i don't know when it was built the old one i believe i believe i was just a hundred and that seemed like they said about 107 years old that's what i heard because we didn't have a
anniversary on the 100th, and the preacher said something about, well, we could have a, have it, you know, for 107 years.
I believe that's about what it's been like.
Not, not in this place, but I mean, since it's organized.
Do you remember anything about church when you were young, and the difference in, in the type services now and then?
Well, uh, church, when I was young, uh,
I know young people didn't have anything to say in the church in them days.
And the ladies didn't need us for that matter.
It was run by the men way back then.
And I remember they had what they called in them days, Amen Corners.
A bunch of men, you know, maybe deacons and men that was active in the church
maybe four or five benches in the corner over here, and people called that Amen Corners.
When preachers got preaching pretty hard, preaching the truth, well, they'd amen him, you know.
You don't hear much of that no more.
You ever sit in an Amen corner?
No.
No, I don't.
That is kind of, when I got up, kind of out of date, like.
You know, a big part of any community are the
the people that are in the politics of the community, the mayors, the judges, you've already mentioned one, the city councils, councilmen, that sort of thing.
Do you remember any particularly important people having held positions in Bryan College Station outside this judge you mentioned a moment ago?
If so, tell me something about them that you remember.
I'm sure there's been a lot of them, but I, you know, we lived out here and we didn't, we don't even get to vote on that city
officers out there and things like that.
I don't know.
I just never did get interested.
Like I said, we just didn't have any say coming out there about the mayor and things like that.
Do you remember any scandals, any crimes that were found out?
There's Watergate on the national scale.
Did Bryan College Station ever have anything that way that you can remember?
No, I can't remember.
I just don't remember any crimes.
What kind of games did you play when you were a kid?
I'm sure they must differ from the games kids play today.
Well, when we were youngsters, they had play parties.
When school was out for the holidays during Christmas,
Every night, you know, they'd usually wait until it turned out, oh, you'd have a week or ten days, holidays, Christmas.
But every, uh, for every night during that time, except Sunday night, they'd have a, have a party.
Different people, you know, they'd like to have a party here tonight and down yard tomorrow night and somewhere else.
But they'd have one sort of lined out for every night.
And, uh,
The game they played them, it sure would look silly.
Tell me about it.
Tell me about it, really.
You'd take an old boy and they'd play what you call a snap.
You know, a boy and girl would hold hands and say a girl would snap somebody.
Well, you'd run around and around that couple that's holding hands until you could tag him.
And then he'd hold up with her.
And then they'd...
tag, I mean, ask somebody to come catch them.
Now that don't make sense, but we've done that a million times.
And they had the, we had one game that they pulled, I don't think I've ever seen them pull that but once.
But they have two chairs like sitting together right here, three chairs.
and they'd put a quilt over all three of them.
Not that they had two chairs, but it'd be fixed like there's three and the middle would be vacant.

And there'd be two girls maybe sitting here and this one and that one over there and they'd bring an old boy in, have him blindfolded, you know, call him in and lead him up there and take the blindfold.
Well, no, they didn't have him blindfolded.
They'd just bring him in there and they'd tell him,
Sit down there between them two girls and have a tub of water under there.
When he'd sit down, when the girls start to sit down, the girls jump up.
Put right down the tub of water, he'd go.
The continuation of this tape is on the flip side.
